&lt;h2&gt;Wednesday, 14 September 2005&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;section id="slow-times-at-gold-rush-games"&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Slow Times at Gold Rush Games&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I ran across a reference to a post from 2004 explaining &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.goldrushgames.com/"&gt;Gold Rush
Games&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a class="reference external" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20040803005822/http://www.goldrushgames.com/forums/index.php?act=ST&amp;amp;f=2&amp;amp;t=384"&gt;current plans&lt;/a&gt;.
It's a pity the roleplaying games industry is such a difficult place
to make a living.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;section id="publishing-on-demand"&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Publishing On Demand&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I also ran across an article that gives some of the &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://www.locusmag.com/2004/Features/03Wallace_PODEssay.html"&gt;reasons&lt;/a&gt;
that Print-On-Demand hasn't been the success that many expected.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
&lt;section id="savanti-books-edition-of-dray-prescott-books"&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;Savanti Books Edition of Dray Prescott Books&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The most recent &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://groups.yahoo.com/group/Kregen/message/16632"&gt;summary&lt;/a&gt; of the
situation with the Savanti Books edition of the Dray is dismal but not
surprising.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/section&gt;
